{
  "texts": [
    "k(x, x ′) = ⟨ϕ(x), ϕ(x ′)⟩ H for some (typically implicit) feature map ϕ.",
    "A positive definite kernel k: X ×X → R on an input space X implicitly defines an RKHS H k in which linear algorithms operate via Gram matrices K ij = k(x i, x j) (the \"kernel trick\") [20,21].",
    "In GPs, the kernel plays the role of a covariance function that encodes prior smoothness and inductive bias; posterior predictions follow in closed form given K and a likelihood [19].",
    "Consequently, the modelling power of a GP hinges on choosing a kernel tailored to the structure of the inputs (e.g.",
    "strings, graphs, molecules), rather than generic Euclidean distances."
  ]
}